{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f15523cd-fd07-4e39-a7b2-df13f001d338","content":"I don't see a `.dmp` file in the current directory, and `dotnet-dump` isn't installed yet. Here's what I recommend:\n\n### To analyze your dump, you'll need:\n\n1. **Install `dotnet-dump`:**\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n   ```\n\n2. **Open your dump:**\n   ```bash\n   dotnet-dump analyze /path/to/your-file.dmp\n   ```\n\n3. **Key commands inside the analyzer:**\n   | Command | Purpose |\n   |---------|---------|\n   | `clrstack` | Managed call stack of crashing thread |\n   | `pe` (or `printexception`) | Print the last exception |\n   | `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n   | `dso` (or `dumpstackobjects`) | Objects on the stack |\n   | `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (for memory issues) |\n\n### Typical root-cause workflow:\n```\n> pe                  # see the exception\n> clrstack            # see where it happened\n> clrthreads          # check for deadlocks/thread issues\n> setthread <id>      # switch to a specific thread\n> clrstack            # inspect that thread's stack\n```\n\n**Want me to install `dotnet-dump` and run the analysis?** If so, please share the path to your `.dmp` file (or copy it into this directory).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bd6ffe9b-a3db-4507-a975-a6f7d5825f93","outputTokens":348,"requestId":"9423:2544DD:2BDD10:33BCAD:69E82171"},"id":"de3897ad-1c64-4eac-af81-c232c41bd414","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:16:53.924Z","parentId":"b9fb04ce-e3be-46a3-bc41-93103eb0fd16"}
